    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-02-21T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-02-21T17:00:00-05:00" n="886"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d886">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense(M)Turkey/838: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-02-21T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >February 21, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>135. Department fully shares FEA’s<note n="10" xml:id="d886fn10">Foreign Economic
                        Administration.</note> expressed concern over substantially increased rate
                    of Turkish chrome shipments to Germany during past 3 months. We understand from
                    British here that your British colleague has lodged a protest with Minister for
                    Foreign Affairs. After consultation with your British colleague, please make <pb
                        facs="0832" n="820" xml:id="pg_820"/> such representations or take such
                    action as you jointly agree would be most effective. In this connection
                    assurances given Embassy last fall and reported in Embassy’s 1720 of October
                        18<note n="11" xml:id="d886fn11">
                        <ref target="frus1943v04#pg_1165">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1943, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, p. 1165</ref>.</note> would appear to
                    provide secure basis for vigorous protest.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
